<DOC><DOCNO> AP900129-0179 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-29-90 2327EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Israel-MiG     01-29 0244</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Israel-MiG,0252</SECOND><HEAD>Israel Tests Soviet Fighter Jet Flown There by Syrian Defector</HEAD><DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An air force pilot test flew a Soviet-madeMiG-23 fighter jet on Monday in its first flight since a Syrianpilot defected to Israel in it last October.   The Israeli flew the jet for about 50 minutes and performed aseries of maneuvers, including a flyover of Jerusalem. An F-15 andan F-16, both U.S.-made fighter jets, escorted the MiG-23.   ``We are investigating the systems to see what they do and seehow we can work against them,'' the pilot told reporters later.``It means a lot to us.''   His name could not be disclosed under briefing rules.   He said the Syrian pilot, Maj. Mohammed Bassam Adel, instructedhim on operating the aircraft. Adel, 34, flew it to Israel on Oct.11, saying he sought freedom.   When the jet was put on display Monday, it carried its originalcamouflage colors. The Syrian flag remained on its tail, but ablue-and-white Star of David was painted on its fuselage.   A senior air force officer said the jet was the only one of itsclass in the West. He indicated that information gleaned from thetest could be exchanged with friendly nations.   Israeli sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, saidAmerican experts from the Pentagon, U.S. Air Force and intelligenceagencies recently visited Israel to inspect the MiG-23.   Defense Ministry spokesman Eitan Haber refused to comment on anysuch visit.</TEXT></DOC>